The article discusses President Biden's commitment to making communities safer through investing in community policing and crime prevention. The plan emphasizes the need for funding police officers who are familiar with the neighborhood and accountable to the community. It also highlights the importance of investing in mental health and substance use treatment services, crisis responders, and social workers to alleviate the burden on police officers and prevent violent crime. The plan further emphasizes the expansion of community violence interventions led by trusted individuals who can break the cycle of violence and trauma. Additionally, the article mentions the need to enforce gun laws, including background checks for all gun sales and banning assault weapons and high-capacity magazines. President Biden's fiscal year 2023 budget requests approximately $35 billion to support law enforcement and crime prevention, in addition to a $2 billion discretionary request. The Safer America Plan outlines how this funding will be utilized to enhance community safety and save lives.